a Colonna in Rinaldo Corso’s Tutte le rime (1558) -- tPart 6. Impact -- t13. Colonna and Petrarch in the Rime of Lucia Colao -- t14. ‘I Take Thee’: Vittoria Colonna, Conjugal Verse and Male poeti colonnesi -- t15. ‘She Showed the World a Beacon of Female Worth’ : Vittoria Colonna in Arcadia -- tVolume Bibliography -- tIndex of Citations of Colonna’s Letters and Verse -- tThematic Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis edited collection presents fresh and original work on Vittoria Colonna, perhaps the outstanding female figure of the Italian Renaissance, a leading Petrarchist poet, and an important figure in the Italian Reform movement. Until recently best known for her close spiritual friendship with Michelangelo, she is increasingly recognized as a powerful and distinctive poetic voice, a cultural and religious icon, and an important literary model for both men and women. This volume comprises compelling new research by established and emerging scholars in the fields of literature, book history, religious history, and art history, including several studies of Colonna’s influence during the Counter-Reformation, a period long neglected by Italian cultural historiography. The Colonna who emerges from this new reading is one who challenges traditional constructions of women’s place in Italian literature; no mere imitator or follower, but an innovator and founder of schools in her own right.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aEuropean history: Renaissance. 4aGender and Sexuality Studies. 4aGender studies: women and girls. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aLiterary studies: c 1400 to c 1600. 4aRenaissance style. 4ac 1400 to c 1499 (period of the